posts.name: Fletch
posts.cooked:
Well right now, your code tells it not to run …

Can you explain what you’re trying to do? You don’t really need enableDigital(). Thats the default mode and will happen automatically simply by instantiating a Solenoid/DoubleSolenoid object.  If you NEED to get the state of the compressor for some reason, you can create that object, but otherwise theres no need to do so at all.

posts.name: NewtonCrosby
posts.cooked:
Read the documentation for the Compressor object you’re instantiating.

From that documentation:

The module will automatically run in closed loop mode by default whenever a Solenoid object is created. For most cases, a Compressor object does not need to be instantiated or used in a robot program. This class is only required in cases where the robot program needs a more detailed status of the compressor or to enable/disable closed loop control.

And just in case you’re wondering, this applies to DoubleSolenoid objects as well.

So step one, remove the compressor object altogether unless you are doing something specifically that requires it.

Question: Why do you have your solenoid channels in different sets?  We typically just wire a Double solenoid in channels 0,1; 2,3; 4,5 and so on.  0,7, and 1,6 just seems off too me.

posts.name: MrHill_6975
posts.cooked: It’s because they feed into a manifold. The wires line up nicer they are allocated this way.

posts.name: SLAB-Mr.Thomas
posts.cooked: It’s hard to follow the circuits in the photo but you need to verify that you don’t have the pressure limit switch and compressor power circuits reversed.  Where’s @bovlb when you need him? He’s the wizard at following impossible to follow wiring.

posts.name: Gavin Matthews
posts.cooked:
What I can see of the wiring looks good to me.  (But please make sure you’re using 18 AWG between the PDB/PDH and the PCM.  Also, I can see bare metal on a main breaker terminal.)  I don’t see any air storage tanks; I would not expect the pressure switch to operate correctly without them.

A test you might like to perform is to bridge the terminals on the pressure switch.  See How to Adjust the Pressure Relief Valve - YouTube .

posts.name: Gavin Matthews
posts.cooked:
Um, unless I’m missing something, you have both your air cylinders and your solenoids downstream of the pressure vent plug, and I cannot see any pressure regulator.

Have a look at the picture on p108 of the manual (R805) and see also the (slightly outdated) Pneumatics Manual .
